PARAMETER PROPERTIES are a TypeScript shorthand for declaring and initializing class properties in the constructor:

Without shorthand:
```typescript
class User {
  public name: string;
  private age: number;
  constructor(name: string, age: number) {
    this.name = name; this.age = age;
  }
}
```

With parameter property shorthand:
```typescript
class User {
  constructor(
    public name: string,
    private age: number
  ) {} // TypeScript creates the properties and assigns them automatically
}
```

Any access modifier (`public`, `private`, `protected`, `readonly`) in the constructor parameter position activates this shorthand. This is TypeScript-only and saves a lot of boilerplate.

The `override` keyword (TS 4.3+) is used in subclasses to explicitly declare that a method OVERRIDES a parent method:

```typescript
class Animal {
  makeSound() { return 'generic sound'; }
}

class Dog extends Animal {
  override makeSound() { return 'woof'; }         // OK
  override fly() { return 'dogs can fly'; }       // Error! fly() doesn't exist in Animal
}
```

With `noImplicitOverride: true` in tsconfig, TypeScript REQUIRES `override` on any method that overrides a parent method. This prevents accidental overrides and catches typos in method names.

Benefit: if you rename `makeSound` to `emit` in `Animal`, TypeScript immediately tells you that `Dog.override makeSound` no longer overrides anything.

TypeScript (like JavaScript) only supports SINGLE inheritance through `extends`. MIXINS solve the need to compose multiple behaviours without full multiple inheritance:

```typescript
type Constructor<T = {}> = new (...args: any[]) => T;

function Serializable<TBase extends Constructor>(Base: TBase) {
  return class extends Base {
    serialize() { return JSON.stringify(this); }
  };
}

function Timestamped<TBase extends Constructor>(Base: TBase) {
  return class extends Base {
    createdAt = new Date();
  };
}

class User { constructor(public name: string) {} }
const TimestampedUser = Timestamped(Serializable(User));
const u = new TimestampedUser('Alice');
u.serialize();    // from Serializable
u.createdAt;      // from Timestamped
u.name;           // from User
```

Mixins are higher-order functions over classes. TypeScript fully types the result.

• `extends`: inherits the IMPLEMENTATION (methods, properties, constructor) from a parent class. Establishes a prototype chain at runtime.

• `implements`: a COMPILE-TIME CHECK that the class satisfies the listed interface/type contracts. TypeScript verifies the class has the required shape but provides NO implementation or runtime behavior.

```typescript
interface Printable { print(): void; }
interface Serializable { serialize(): string; }

class Doc extends BaseDoc implements Printable, Serializable {
  print() { console.log(this.content); }    // required by Printable
  serialize() { return JSON.stringify(this); } // required by Serializable
}
```

A class can `implements` MULTIPLE interfaces. `implements` generates NO JavaScript output at all — it's purely a type check.

DECORATORS are special functions applied to classes, methods, properties, or parameters using `@decorator` syntax. They ARE emitted in the JavaScript output — they run at class definition time.

```typescript
@Injectable() // decorator — modifies the class
class UserService {
  @Inject(Database)  // parameter decorator
  constructor(private db: Database) {}

  @Log()  // method decorator
  getUser(id: string) { ... }
}
```

`emitDecoratorMetadata: true` makes TypeScript emit `Reflect.metadata` calls that attach type information (like constructor parameter types) to the class. Frameworks like Angular, NestJS, and TypeORM rely on this to implement dependency injection — they read the types to automatically inject the right dependencies.

Requires `experimentalDecorators: true` (legacy) or uses the new TC39 Stage 3 decorator syntax in TS 5.0+.
